WEBVTT

00:00:01.200 --> 00:00:07.920
<v Teacher>So again, <i>You're staying here</i>. Let's make that. <i>You're staying here</i>, informal.

00:00:07.920 --> 00:00:09.600
<v Student><b>Te quedas aquí</b>.

00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:11.040
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Te quedas aquí</b>. <i>You're not staying here</i>:

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:15.280
<v Student><b>No te quedas aquí</b>.

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:16.880
<v Teacher><b>No te quedas aquí</b>. Or <b>acá</b>.

00:00:16.880 --> 00:00:22.000
<v Teacher>Now, if you want to make that a question, <i>Aren't you staying here</i>?:

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:24.080
<v Student>¿<b>No te quedas aquí</b>?

00:00:24.080 --> 00:00:24.480
<v Teacher>Good. ¿<b>No te quedas aquí</b>?

00:00:24.480 --> 00:00:27.520
<v Teacher><i>Why aren't you staying here</i>?:

00:00:27.520 --> 00:00:29.760
<v Student>¿<b>Por qué no te quedas aquí</b>?

00:00:29.760 --> 00:00:30.880
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:00:30.880 --> 00:00:35.040
<v Teacher>What was <i>I go</i> or <i>I'm going</i>? (<i>I'm going</i> on a <i>voyage</i>.)

00:00:35.040 --> 00:00:36.340
<v Student><b>Voy</b>.

00:00:36.340 --> 00:00:41.460
<v Teacher><b>Voy</b>. Good. So, how do you think you would say <i>I'm going to stay</i>, <i>I'm going to remain myself</i>?

00:00:44.340 --> 00:00:46.260
<v Student><b>Voy a quedarme</b>.

00:00:46.260 --> 00:00:49.220
<v Teacher>Good. <i>Until seven</i>, <i>until seven o'clock</i>.

00:00:49.220 --> 00:00:54.260
<v Teacher><i>Seven</i> is <b>siete</b>, similar to the beginning of <i>September</i>.

00:00:54.260 --> 00:01:01.500
<v Teacher><i>September</i> in Spanish actually is either <b>Septiembre</b> or <b>Setiembre</b>. You have two versions of it in Spanish,

00:01:01.500 --> 00:01:05.020
<v Teacher><b>Septiembre</b> with the <i>p</i>, or without the <i>p</i>, <b>Setiembre</b>.

00:01:05.020 --> 00:01:10.439
<v Teacher>And you can see how <b>siete</b> is like the beginning "set" with the split of the <i>e</i>.

00:01:10.439 --> 00:01:18.759
<v Teacher>So, <i>I'm going to stay</i>, <i>I'm going to remain myself until seven o'clock</i>. <i>I'm going to stay until seven o'clock</i>:

00:01:18.759 --> 00:01:23.760
<v Student><b>Voy a quedarme hasta las siete</b>.

00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:27.680
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Voy a quedarme hasta las siete</b>. Very good.

00:01:27.680 --> 00:01:30.080
<v Teacher>How do you say <i>I want to stay</i>?

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:32.860
<v Student><b>Quiero quedarme</b>.

00:01:32.860 --> 00:01:33.100
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:33.100 --> 00:01:35.740
<v Teacher><b>Quiero quedarme</b>. Good. <i>Do you want to stay</i>?

00:01:35.740 --> 00:01:39.340
<v Teacher>Let's talk informally. <i>Do you want to stay</i>?:

00:01:39.940 --> 00:01:42.260
<v Student>¿<b>Quieres quedarte</b>?

00:01:42.260 --> 00:01:44.900
<v Teacher>Good. Very good. ¿<b>Quieres quedarte</b>?

00:01:44.900 --> 00:01:47.140
<v Teacher><i>Do you want to remain yourself</i>?

00:01:47.140 --> 00:01:49.940
<v Teacher>What was <i>I must</i> or <i>I owe</i>?

00:01:50.740 --> 00:01:51.700
<v Student><b>Debo</b>.

00:01:51.700 --> 00:01:57.299
<v Teacher><b>Debo</b>. Good. What is <i>we owe</i> or <i>we must</i>?

00:01:57.299 --> 00:02:01.220
<v Teacher>And the "to" form is <b>deber</b>. <b>Deber</b>, <i>to owe</i>. So <i>we</i>:

00:02:01.220 --> 00:02:04.960
<v Student><b>Debemos</b>.

00:02:04.960 --> 00:02:07.920
<v Teacher>Good. <i>We must stay</i>.

00:02:07.920 --> 00:02:13.040
<v Teacher>So, <i>We owe to remain ourselves</i>. <i>We must stay</i>:

00:02:14.319 --> 00:02:19.120
<v Student><b>Debemos quedarme</b>, <b>quedarnos</b>.

00:02:19.120 --> 00:02:21.200
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Debemos quedarnos</b>.

00:02:21.200 --> 00:02:24.400
<v Teacher>Of course this <b>nos</b> or <b>me</b> or <b>te</b> can come at the beginning as well.

00:02:24.400 --> 00:02:27.800
<v Teacher><b>Nos debemos quedar</b>, <b>debemos quedarnos</b>. Good.

00:02:27.800 --> 00:02:30.760
<v Teacher>What was <i>I have</i>, in the sense of possession?

00:02:30.760 --> 00:02:33.880
<v Teacher>So not <b>haber</b>, the other "have"?

00:02:33.880 --> 00:02:35.240
<v Student><b>Tengo</b>.

00:02:35.240 --> 00:02:45.220
<v Teacher><b>Tengo</b>. So, if we add on <b>que</b> to <b>tengo</b>, we get the meaning of <i>have to</i>, which is just like <b>debo</b>, but less serious sounding. Just like in English.

00:02:45.220 --> 00:02:49.060
<v Teacher><i>I must stay</i> sounds a little bit more serious than <i>I have to stay</i>.

00:02:49.060 --> 00:02:54.820
<v Teacher>And that difference in register, how it feels, is the same in Spanish.

00:02:54.820 --> 00:02:57.780
<v Teacher>So how do you say <i>I have to stay</i>?

00:02:58.500 --> 00:03:01.060
<v Student><b>Tengo que quedarme</b>.

00:03:01.060 --> 00:03:01.540
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:01.540 --> 00:03:05.700
<v Teacher>And how would you say <i>You have to stay</i>, speaking informally?

00:03:06.540 --> 00:03:09.260
<v Student><b>Tienes que quedarte</b>.

00:03:09.260 --> 00:03:11.579
<v Teacher><b>Tienes que quedarte</b>. Good.

00:03:11.579 --> 00:03:15.819
<v Teacher><i>You have to stay here</i>, informally still:

00:03:16.340 --> 00:03:20.660
<v Student><b>Tienes que quedarte aquí</b>.

00:03:20.660 --> 00:03:24.500
<v Teacher>Good. <i>I want to know why you have to stay here</i>.

00:03:24.500 --> 00:03:25.700
<v Teacher><i>I want to know</i>.

00:03:25.700 --> 00:03:30.260
<v Teacher>First bit: don't think about the whole sentence, just think of <i>I want</i>:

00:03:30.440 --> 00:03:32.600
<v Student><b>Quiero saber</b>.

00:03:32.600 --> 00:03:35.560
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Quiero saber</b>. Now forget that bit. <i>Why</i>:

00:03:36.840 --> 00:03:37.640
<v Student><b>Por qué</b>.

00:03:37.640 --> 00:03:39.720
<v Teacher><i>You have to stay here</i>:

00:03:40.040 --> 00:03:44.360
<v Student><b>Tienes que quedarte aquí</b>.

00:03:44.360 --> 00:03:50.599
<v Teacher>Good. Very good. <b>Quiero saber por qué tienes que quedarte aquí</b>. Good.

00:03:50.599 --> 00:03:55.980
<v Teacher>What was <i>I can</i>, or <i>I have the power to</i>?

00:03:55.980 --> 00:03:57.020
<v Student><b>Puedo</b>.

00:03:57.020 --> 00:03:59.260
<v Teacher><b>Puedo</b>. Good. <i>I can stay</i>:

00:03:59.260 --> 00:04:01.180
<v Student><b>Puedo quedarme</b>.

00:04:01.180 --> 00:04:02.860
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Puedo quedarme</b>.

00:04:02.860 --> 00:04:04.380
<v Teacher><i>I can't stay</i>:

00:04:04.580 --> 00:04:06.100
<v Student><b>No puedo quedarme</b>.

00:04:06.100 --> 00:04:10.980
<v Teacher>Good. <b>No puedo quedarme</b>. Do you remember how to say <i>tonight</i>, or <i>this night</i>?

00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:12.660
<v Student><b>Esta noche</b>.

00:04:12.660 --> 00:04:16.740
<v Teacher><b>Esta noche</b>. Good. <i>I can't stay tonight</i>:

00:04:17.459 --> 00:04:21.859
<v Student><b>No puedo quedarme esta noche</b>.

00:04:21.859 --> 00:04:24.820
<v Teacher>Good. <b>No puedo quedarme esta noche</b>.

00:04:24.820 --> 00:04:30.020
<v Teacher>The "to" form of <i>can</i> is <b>poder</b>, <b>poder</b>. And this <i>o</i> is splitting when we

00:04:30.020 --> 00:04:37.920
<v Teacher>stress it and say <b>puedo</b>. <b>Poder</b>. So how would you say <i>we can</i> or <i>we are able</i>?

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:39.200
<v Student><b>Podemos</b>.

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:41.200
<v Teacher><b>Podemos</b>. Very good.

00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:42.400
<v Teacher><i>We can stay</i>:

00:04:42.400 --> 00:04:44.000
<v Student><b>Podemos quedarnos</b>.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:46.000
<v Teacher><b>Podemos quedarnos</b>. <i>We can't stay tonight</i>:

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:52.480
<v Student><b>No podemos quedarnos esta noche</b>.

00:04:52.480 --> 00:05:00.400
<v Teacher>Good. <b>No podemos quedarnos esta noche</b>.

00:05:00.400 --> 00:05:04.560
<v Teacher>What was <i>to think</i> or <i>to be pensive</i>? <i>To think</i>:

00:05:04.560 --> 00:05:06.260
<v Student><b>Pensar</b>.

00:05:06.260 --> 00:05:07.620
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Pensar</b>. <i>We think</i>:

00:05:07.620 --> 00:05:10.820
<v Student><b>Pensamos</b>.

00:05:10.820 --> 00:05:13.540
<v Teacher>Good. <i>You think</i> (informal)?

00:05:14.240 --> 00:05:15.200
<v Student><b>Pensas</b>.

00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:17.440
<v Teacher>Good, it should be <b>pensas</b>, should—

00:05:17.440 --> 00:05:18.160
<v Student><b>Piensas</b>.

00:05:18.160 --> 00:05:19.680
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Piensas</b>. <i>What do you think</i>?:

00:05:19.680 --> 00:05:21.440
<v Student>¿<b>Qué piensas</b>?

00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:25.120
<v Teacher>¿<b>Qué piensas</b>? Good.

00:05:25.120 --> 00:05:33.920
<v Teacher>Now, if we want to say <i>Do you plan on staying here tonight?</i> we can just say <i>Do you think to stay here tonight?</i> Ah?

00:05:33.920 --> 00:05:38.280
<v Teacher><i>Do you think to stay here tonight?</i> So how would we say this, informally?

00:05:38.280 --> 00:05:42.000
<v Student>¿<b>Piensas quedarte aquí esta noche</b>?

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:47.740
<v Teacher>Good. ¿<b>Piensas quedarte aquí esta noche</b>? Very good.

00:05:47.740 --> 00:05:51.580
<v Teacher>Now how would you say <i>I have stayed</i>?

00:05:51.580 --> 00:05:57.660
<v Teacher><i>I have stayed</i>, or <i>I have remained myself</i>, <i>I have stayed</i>:

00:05:58.360 --> 00:06:01.000
<v Student><b>He quedado me</b>, <b>He me quedado</b>.

00:06:03.080 --> 00:06:08.539
<v Teacher>I don't want you to guess and see what feels good. So with logic you want to place it.

00:06:08.539 --> 00:06:15.099
<v Teacher>And if you're wrong, it's fine, because if you got there through a fault of logic, you'll change the logic through that mistake.

00:06:15.099 --> 00:06:18.539
<v Teacher>So tell me the rule about where that <b>me</b> can go.

00:06:18.900 --> 00:06:23.540
<v Student>It goes after the "to" form. And before everything else.

00:06:23.620 --> 00:06:25.300
<v Teacher>Before the changed verb.

00:06:25.300 --> 00:06:29.140
<v Teacher>It's very important the way we instruct ourselves.

00:06:29.140 --> 00:06:34.920
<v Teacher>Now I'm giving you always the simplest way that we can instruct ourselves accurately.

00:06:34.920 --> 00:06:42.180
<v Teacher>If I tell you "before the verb" and you tell yourself "at the beginning", you lose something. Ah, you lose a certain clarity.

00:06:42.180 --> 00:06:46.420
<v Student>Because nouns might come into the sentence and then—

00:06:46.420 --> 00:06:49.700
<v Teacher>Exactly. <i>We have stayed</i>, <i>we have remained ourselves</i>:

00:06:50.860 --> 00:06:53.500
<v Student><b>Nos hemos quedado</b>.

00:06:53.500 --> 00:06:56.139
<v Teacher>Very good. <b>Nos hemos quedado</b>.

00:06:56.139 --> 00:06:58.060
<v Teacher><i>We haven't stayed</i>:

00:06:59.160 --> 00:07:01.800
<v Student><b>No nos hemos quedado</b>.

00:07:01.800 --> 00:07:05.000
<v Teacher>Very good. <b>No nos hemos quedado</b>.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:09.000
<v Teacher><i>You have stayed</i> (informal). <i>You have stayed</i>:

00:07:09.500 --> 00:07:11.580
<v Student><b>Te has quedado</b>.

00:07:11.580 --> 00:07:15.100
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Te has quedado</b>. Make it a question, <i>Have you stayed</i>?:

00:07:17.180 --> 00:07:18.460
<v Student>¿<b>Te has quedado</b>?

00:07:18.460 --> 00:07:23.420
<v Teacher>Good. And let's be emphatic now, let's say the word for <i>you</i>.

00:07:24.120 --> 00:07:25.720
<v Student>¿<b>Tú te has quedado</b>?

00:07:25.720 --> 00:07:27.480
<v Teacher>Good. ¿<b>Tú te has quedado</b>?

00:07:27.480 --> 00:07:31.880
<v Teacher>Let's make it negative now. <i>Haven't you stayed</i>?:

00:07:35.419 --> 00:07:35.979
<v Student>¿<b>Tú no te has quedado</b>?

00:07:35.979 --> 00:07:39.259
<v Teacher>Good. ¿<b>Tú no te has quedado</b>? Good.

00:07:39.259 --> 00:07:51.759
<v Teacher><b>Llamar</b>, in Spanish, is <i>to call</i>, or <i>to phone</i>, <i>to telephone</i>, <b>llamar</b>. <i>L-l</i>, which we said is pronounced like <i>y</i> in most of the Spanish speaking world. <i>To call</i>.

00:07:51.759 --> 00:07:52.639
<v Student><b>Llamar</b>.

00:07:52.639 --> 00:07:54.880
<v Teacher>How do you say <i>I call</i>?

00:07:54.900 --> 00:07:55.700
<v Student><b>Llamo</b>.

00:07:55.700 --> 00:08:04.980
<v Teacher><b>Llamo</b>. If you want to introduce yourself, instead of saying <i>My name is</i>, in Spanish it's much more common to say <i>I call myself</i>.

00:08:05.800 --> 00:08:06.840
<v Student><b>Me llamo</b>.

00:08:06.840 --> 00:08:09.000
<v Teacher><b>Me llamo</b>. And then you can introduce yourself.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:12.200
<v Teacher><b>Me llamo Mihalis</b>, for example.

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:15.640
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>You call yourself</i> (informal)?

00:08:16.400 --> 00:08:17.840
<v Student><b>Te llamas</b>.

00:08:17.840 --> 00:08:19.200
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Te llamas</b>.

00:08:19.200 --> 00:08:23.200
<v Teacher>If you want to ask the name, you will say <i>How do you call yourself?</i>

00:08:23.200 --> 00:08:26.160
<v Teacher>And the word for <i>how</i> is <b>cómo</b>. <b>Cómo</b>.

00:08:26.160 --> 00:08:27.280
<v Student><b>Cómo</b>.

00:08:27.280 --> 00:08:30.480
<v Teacher>So how do you say <i>How do you call yourself</i>?:

00:08:30.960 --> 00:08:33.120
<v Student>¿<b>Cómo te llamas</b>?

00:08:33.120 --> 00:08:39.440
<v Teacher>Good. ¿<b>Cómo te llamas</b>? You might have heard this around and not understood actually how it's being constructed.

00:08:39.440 --> 00:08:44.320
<v Teacher>Now we understand it. It's <i>How do you call yourself?</i> ¿<b>Cómo te llamas</b>?

